<ArticleLayout
  title="Your Doctor Can't Answer That Either"
  description="The clinical encounter is a room built for 'how.' Patients keep arriving with 'why.' The mismatch is making people sicker. Neither system — conventional or alternative — is covering itself in glory."
  category="Clinical Evidence"
  readTime="24 min read"
  publishDate="March 2026"
>
<div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
<p>The rheumatologist has explained the diagnosis twice now. The pathophysiology is clear, the treatment protocol is established, the prognosis — given adherence to the medication — is genuinely good. The patient is nodding. She has been nodding for eleven minutes.</p>
<p>She is not listening.</p>
<p>She stopped listening somewhere around the third sentence, when it became apparent that the doctor was going to explain what was happening in her joints but not the thing she actually came to find out: why her body has decided, at fifty-three, after decades of reasonable behavior on her part, to turn against her. She wants a reason. A real one. Not a mechanism — a <em>meaning</em>. The doctor has mechanism in abundance and meaning precisely nowhere to hand, and so the consultation proceeds in the polite fiction of two people having the same conversation, while actually having two completely different ones.</p>
<p>She will leave with a prescription she fills but doesn't take consistently, a follow-up appointment she cancels, and a browser history full of searches that will, within a fortnight, deliver her into the hands of someone who does have an answer. Whether that answer is better than the one she just left behind is, as we will see, a genuinely open question. It will feel, for a while, like relief.</p>
<p>This scene plays out in consulting rooms at a scale that the healthcare system has not seriously reckoned with. It is not a communication failure, exactly. It is a structural mismatch between what medicine is equipped to provide and what patients, in distress, most urgently want. And the gap between those two things is wide enough to drive an industry through.</p>
</section>

<section id="what-patients-come-for" class="reveal">
  <h2>What Patients Actually Come For</h2>
<p>There is a concept in health psychology called the <em>illness representation</em> — the mental model a patient constructs, often rapidly and largely unconsciously, to make sense of what is happening to their body. Researchers Leventhal, Meyer, and Nerenz, developing what became known as the Common Sense Model of illness behavior, identified five dimensions patients instinctively want addressed: what is this thing, how long will it last, what caused it, what consequences will it have, and can it be controlled?</p>
<p>Of these five, the third — cause — turns out to exert disproportionate influence on everything else. Patients who have a causal explanation they believe, even a wrong one, show better treatment adherence, lower anxiety, and higher satisfaction with care than patients who have accurate information without a satisfying cause story. The explanation is not doing epistemic work. It is doing emotional work. It is closing the loop. And a closed loop, the brain will take from almost any source, at almost any cost to accuracy.</p>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">Research Note</h4>
  <p>In a now-classic study by Weinman and colleagues, patients recovering from myocardial infarction who believed their heart attack had a specific, controllable cause — even an incorrect one — returned to work faster and reported better recovery outcomes than those who held ambiguous or fatalistic causal beliefs. The belief that something <em>caused</em> the event, and that the cause was in some sense addressable, was itself therapeutic. The content of the belief mattered less than its structure.</p>
</div>

<p>This is what medicine is up against. Patients are not primarily rational actors seeking accurate information and making evidence-based decisions. They are meaning-seeking organisms in distress, and the clinical encounter — which is optimized for information transfer, not meaning-making — is often a poor match for what they actually need. Doctors know this, intuitively, and are largely untrained to do anything about it. The result is a consultation that satisfies neither party and a patient who leaves technically informed and existentially empty.</p>
</section>

<section id="doctors-wrong" class="reveal">
  <h2>What Doctors Get Wrong — And How Often</h2>
<p>It is worth pausing here, before any comparison between conventional and alternative medicine, to be honest about what conventional medicine actually is — not in its best-case idealized form, but in routine practice.</p>
<p>Medical knowledge has a half-life. A substantial body of research, including a widely cited analysis by researchers at the Mayo Clinic, suggests that up to 40% of established medical practices, when rigorously tested, turn out to be ineffective or actively harmful. Hormone replacement therapy. Routine episiotomy. Arthroscopic knee surgery for osteoarthritis. Antiarrhythmic drugs post-heart attack. Bed rest for back pain. These were not fringe treatments — they were standard of care, delivered with full clinical confidence, for years or decades, before the evidence finally caught up.</p>
<p>The pipeline from research to clinical practice runs slowly and inconsistently. Studies suggest it takes an average of seventeen years for a significant research finding to be routinely incorporated into clinical care. In the meantime, patients receive yesterday's medicine from physicians who are, in many cases, working from a knowledge base that peaked around the time they finished their residency. Medical school ends. The reading, for most practitioners, largely does too — not out of laziness, necessarily, but because the system provides almost no structure for sustained learning once the license is granted and the loans start coming due.</p>
<p>This is not an outlier problem. It is a structural one. A physician twelve years out of training, seeing thirty patients a day in a fifteen-minute appointment model, updating their practice based primarily on what pharmaceutical representatives tell them and what colleagues happen to mention at conferences — this is not a broken doctor. It is a statistically average one.</p>
<p>Conventional medicine also provides why-answers — it just packages them as diagnoses, which grants them an authority they don't always deserve. <em>This runs in your family.</em> Four words that can install a fatalism indistinguishable from a life sentence, leading patients to under-treat conditions that are thoroughly manageable because they've been handed a narrative in which management is beside the point. <em>Stress caused this</em> — a phrase so overused it has become medical background noise, but received by the patient as a causal explanation for their autoimmune condition or their cancer, carrying an implicit accusation: you did this to yourself. <em>There's nothing more we can do</em> — a sentence that patients hear as a final verdict on their body, often delivered when the speaker means only that they, personally, have run out of ideas.</p>
<p>The literature on <em>nocebo effects</em> — the measurable harm caused by negative expectations installed by clinical communication — is substantial and underreported. What you are told about your prognosis shapes your prognosis. The authority with which a physician delivers a why-answer gives it a physiological weight the physician, walking to their next appointment, will never witness.</p>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Patients deserve both the attention and the accuracy. A healthcare system that reliably provided the first would have far less to answer for when it comes to the second."</p></aside>
</section>

<section id="alternative" class="reveal">
  <h2>What Alternative Medicine Gets Right — And Where It Goes Wrong</h2>
<p>Against this backdrop — a conventional system that is frequently wrong, structurally resistant to updating, and has largely optimized the humanity out of the clinical encounter — it becomes considerably harder to maintain the comfortable hierarchy in which mainstream medicine occupies the position of rigorous truth and everything else is wishful thinking.</p>
<p>Alternative medicine contains genuine quackery. This needs to be said plainly, because avoiding it is its own form of condescension. There are practitioners operating at the fringes — and sometimes not the fringes — who are selling unproven treatments to desperately ill people, discouraging evidence-based care, and in some cases causing direct harm. The anti-vaccine movement has killed children. Certain cancer patients have died pursuing treatments that had no mechanism of action while declining ones that did. These are not minor footnotes. They are serious failures with serious consequences, and the people responsible for them deserve exactly the scrutiny they receive.</p>
<p>But the honest picture is more complicated than a simple ranking of credibility. A naturopath operating with genuine integrity — taking a thorough history, attending to lifestyle, treating the patient as a whole person, acknowledging uncertainty while staying current with evidence — may well be providing better care, for certain conditions, than a rushed physician working from outdated protocols and a fifteen-minute appointment structure. Meanwhile, a conventional oncologist can be evidence-based in their treatment selection and catastrophically damaging in how they communicate it. The credential does not determine the quality.</p>
<p>What alternative medicine has consistently understood, and what conventional medicine has consistently undervalued, is that the consultation itself is a clinical event. The naturopath has forty-five minutes, takes a comprehensive history that includes life events, relationships, sleep, and meaning, and connects these into a coherent narrative that treats the patient as a situated human being rather than a cluster of presenting complaints. This is not theater. This is, in substantial ways, what good medicine actually looks like — and the fact that the conventional system has largely abandoned it under the pressure of throughput and reimbursement structures is an institutional failure of the first order.</p>
<p>Where things become genuinely complicated — and this is where the honest accounting gets hard — is when the attentive, humanizing consultation is attached to a mechanistic explanation that isn't supported, or a treatment that works primarily through the therapeutic relationship rather than the proposed mechanism. The forty-five minutes of careful listening is real and clinically meaningful. Adrenal fatigue as a diagnosis is not. Patients deserve both the attention <em>and</em> the accuracy — and the frustrating reality is that neither system currently provides both reliably.</p>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The credential does not determine the quality. A naturopath staying current and thinking carefully may be providing better care for certain conditions than a physician working from protocols that peaked in 2003."</p></aside>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">By the Numbers</h4>
  <ul>
    <li>Americans spend approximately <strong>$34 billion annually</strong> on complementary and alternative medicine, according to NIH estimates — a figure that has grown steadily for two decades.</li>
    <li>In surveys of patients who use alternative practitioners, the most commonly cited reason is not dissatisfaction with conventional treatment <em>outcomes</em> but with conventional treatment <em>communication</em> — patients want more time, more explanation, and more engagement with their whole lives.</li>
    <li>The second most cited reason: they felt genuinely listened to.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>That this is considered an alternative experience says something important about what we've built.</p>
</div>
</section>

<section id="patients-best" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Patients Who Actually Do Best</h2>
<p>The most durable finding in health psychology on recovery and long-term disease management is not what you would expect, given the cultural emphasis on positive thinking, spiritual acceptance, and finding meaning in illness.</p>
<p>The patients who do best — by measures of treatment adherence, functional recovery, quality of life, and in some conditions actual clinical outcomes — are not those who found the most satisfying why-answer. They are those who developed what researchers call <em>illness coherence</em>: a working, practical model of how their condition behaves. What triggers it. What moderates it. What they can influence and what they cannot. How to read their own signals. How to communicate with their clinical team in terms of what is actually changing rather than what it means.</p>
<p>This is a how-framework. It is decidedly unglamorous. It does not answer the question of why a good person got a bad disease, or what the universe intends by it, or whether the suffering has a purpose. It answers the question of what happens next, and what you can do about it. It is, in the data, what actually helps.</p>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The patients who recover best are not those who found the most satisfying explanation for their illness. They are the ones who stopped waiting for one."</p></aside>
</section>

<section id="differently" class="reveal">
  <h2>What Medicine Could Do Differently</h2>
<p>There is a small but serious movement within medicine that takes this problem seriously. Rita Charon at Columbia University has spent decades developing what she calls <em>narrative medicine</em> — a clinical approach that trains physicians to elicit and engage with a patient's illness narrative rather than treating it as irrelevant background noise. The patient's story of their illness, in this framework, is not a preamble to the real consultation. It is clinically important data about how they understand their condition, what meaning they have already assigned, and where the gaps and distortions are.</p>
<p>This is not soft. It is diagnostically useful. A patient who believes their cancer was caused by a specific life event — a divorce, a career failure, an unresolved grief — is a patient whose treatment engagement will be shaped by that belief. A physician who knows this can work with it. A physician who doesn't will be puzzled when the patient stops treatment in the middle of a response.</p>
<p>What the evidence also shows is that patients do not, in fact, need a why-answer to feel well-treated. They need to feel that their why-hunger has been acknowledged. The physician who says "I can't tell you why this happened to you, and I think that's genuinely hard, and here is what I can tell you about what's happening and what we can do about it" is, in patient experience research, rated more highly than the physician who provides a confident wrong causal explanation. The acknowledgment of the unanswerable is itself therapeutic — provided it is followed by competent engagement with the answerable.</p>
</section>

<section id="bring-appointment" class="reveal">
  <h2>What to Bring to the Appointment</h2>
<p>For a readership that will see a doctor before they see a philosopher, some of this can be made practical.</p>
<p>The why-hunger is real, and it will be in the room with you. It is worth knowing, before you go in, that the why you are actually asking — not <em>what mechanism</em>, but <em>why me, why now, why at all</em> — is a question no one in that room can answer. The biology may be partially understood. The meaning is not on offer from anyone, in either system.</p>
<p>The questions that will actually serve you in a clinical setting are how-questions. How does this condition typically progress? How will I know if the treatment is working? How does lifestyle interact with this — specifically, in my case? What should I be paying attention to? What can I influence? A good physician can answer these. So, often, can a good integrative practitioner. The standard for both should be the same: current evidence, honest uncertainty, and a willingness to say "I don't know" rather than filling the gap with something that sounds confident.</p>
<p>The why-hunger needs feeding somewhere. That is legitimate. But it belongs in a different room — with a therapist who is actually good at their job, a community of people with the same condition, a spiritual practice, a close friend who will sit with you in the uncertainty rather than rushing to fill it. The clinical encounter is not that room. It was never built for that purpose. Knowing this in advance is not a concession to nihilism. It is a form of practical intelligence.</p>
</section>

<section id="limits" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Limits of the Room</h2>
<p>Neither system, looked at honestly, is covering itself in glory. Conventional medicine has the better epistemology — in principle — but applies it inconsistently, updates slowly, communicates poorly, and has industrialized the clinical relationship to a degree that would strike any previous generation of physicians as malpractice of a different kind. Alternative medicine often has the better relationship with its patients, but a worse relationship with evidence, and at its worst exploits the very human need for meaning that conventional medicine failed to address.</p>
<p>What this means practically is that the intelligent patient navigates both systems critically rather than deferring to either. You bring the same skeptical curiosity to a rheumatologist's confident pronouncement that you bring to a naturopath's root-cause explanation. You ask both: how do you know this? What's the evidence? What would change your mind? Is this treatment being recommended because it's the best available option, or because it's what you were trained to do, or because it's what you sell?</p>
<p>The why-hunger will be present in every room you enter for your healthcare. No one in that room — neither the white coat nor the wellness practitioner — can answer it in the terms in which you're actually asking. What the best of them can do is acknowledge it honestly, and then do competent, current, genuinely curious work on the questions they actually can address.</p>
<p>That combination — honesty about the limits, real competence within them — is rarer than it should be, in either system. When you find it, hold onto it. It is, in the data, better for your health than the most satisfying explanation anyone could offer.</p>
</section>

